":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]},{"name":"Guiver","meanings":["English: (i) nickname, apparently from Middle English  <i>giver</i> ‘giver, donor, bestower’. (ii) variant of   Giffard   with voicing of /f/ to /v/ and loss of final  <i>-d</i>."]},{"name":"Gafford","meanings":["English (southeastern): assimilated form of <b>Gatford</b>, a name of various origins. In Sussex and Surrey it is perhaps a variant of the habitational name <b>Catford</b> from a place so called in Somerset. <b>Gatford</b> is also from the habitational names Gateford (in Worksop, Nottinghamshire) or Gateforth (near Selby, Yorkshire), both formed with Old English <i>gāt</i> ‘goat’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’, influenced by Old Norse <i>geit</i> ‘goat’.","Probably also an altered form of German <b>Gaffert</b>: habitational name from Gaffert near Köslin, Brandenburg, or from a personal name formed with Middle High German <i>gate</i> ‘fellow, companion’. The surname <i>Gaffert</i> is very rare in Germany.","English: perhaps an altered form of   Gatewood  , an occupational name for a ‘goatherd’ (Middle English <i>gate-werde</i>, Old English <i>gātweard</i>) or for a ‘gate keeper’ (Middle English <i>gateward</i>, Old English <i>ʒeatweard</i>, dialect <i>gātward</i>)."]},{"name":"Gifford","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): variant of <b>Giffard</b>, either from the Middle English personal name <i>Gifard</i>, derived from an Old French name of this form deriving from ancient Germanic <i>geb-</i> ‘give, gift’ + <i>hard-</i> ‘hardy, brave’, or perhaps sometimes a nickname from Old French <i>gif(f)ard</i> ‘chubby-cheeked, bloated’."]},{"name":"Jefferd","meanings":["English:  see  Giffard  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705197,"age":46,"year":"1455","julianDay":2252488,"title":"Wars of the Roses","description":"Wars of the Roses was a series of English civil wars for control of the throne of England between the royal families House of Lancaster and the House of York. The name of the war was derived as the red rose was the symbol of the Lancastrians and the white rose was the symbol of the Yorks.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/british-history/wars-of-the-roses","urlTitle":"History - Wars of the Roses","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Giffard was born on 29 September 1408, in Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Roger Giffard, was 41 and his mother, Isabella de Stretley, was 33. He married Eleanor de Vaux in 1429, in England. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died on 29 May 1469, in his hometown, at the age of 60, and was buried in Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England."},"et":{"29 September 1408–29 May 1469":"29. september 1408–29. mai 1469","1405–1430":"1405–1430","1408–1469":"1408–1469","1410–1507":"1410–1507","1410–Female":"1410–Surnud","1405–1478":"1405–1478","1431–1506":"1431–1506","1433–Female":"1433–Surnud","1367–1409":"1367–1409","1375–1415":"1375–1415","7 January 1409":"7. jaanuar 1409","29 September 1408":"29. september 1408","29 May 1469":"29. mai 1469","1415":"1415","1469":"1469","14 April 1409":"14. aprill 1409","1478":"1478","1433":"1433","1455":"1455","1367":"1367","1410":"1410","1431":"1431","1375":"1375","1430":"1430","1407   3rd wife":"märts 1407","1409":"1409","1507":"1507","1408":"1408","1429":"1429","1506":"1506","1405":"1405","England":"England","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England":"Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England","Twyford, Buckinghamshire, England."